# NET-NEW under lead-eqao (P1 launcher bug, THIRD F3 cycle). Pins the EMPIRICAL FINDING
# (product authority, 2026-06-28, REAL flagless v0.3.35 launch of shopsystem-test-harness;
# bc-base fd00496d, bc-container 0.3.35): F1 (manifest-remote resolution, scenario 65) and
# F2 (/workspace ownership, scenario 67) WORK, and the CA IS now materialized correctly —
# /home/vscode/.config/agent-vault/ca.pem exists, vscode-owned, 574 bytes, first line is the
# BEGIN-CERTIFICATE marker. The ONLY remaining bug is the shipped agent-vault-ca.sh's OWN
# post-write VALIDATION step: it runs grep with the BEGIN-CERTIFICATE marker as the PATTERN,
# whose leading dashes make grep parse it as OPTIONS ("grep: unrecognized option ..."), so the
# script falsely concludes "missing BEGIN CERTIFICATE", fail-loud REFUSES to point git at the
# (actually-valid) CA, and the clone never runs. Reproduced in-container: grep with the dash-
# prefixed pattern errors; grep with an end-of-options "--" before the pattern matches.
#
# WHY A COMPANION TO 69, NOT A SUPERSEDE OF 69 (@scenario_hash:09f871cf8b99a34b):
#   69 pins the END-STATE observable — a non-empty CA file beginning with the BEGIN-CERTIFICATE
#   marker AT the path git is configured to trust, git's CA config naming that existing file, and
#   the proxied clone passing TLS. That end-state pin is CORRECT and stays: the CA file is in fact
#   materialized correctly now, so 69's assertions are not wrong. The recurring failure is a
#   TEST-FIDELITY GAP, not a wrong end-state: 69 PASSED the BC suite three F3 cycles running while
#   the REAL shipped agent-vault-ca.sh validation fails, because the BC's test validated the CA
#   with a DIFFERENT (working) check than the shipped script uses — it never exercised the actual
#   shipped validation step. Superseding 69 would discard a correct end-state pin and would not, by
#   itself, close the gap. So we ADD a companion that binds the one thing the three cycles' tests
#   kept bypassing: the REAL shipped agent-vault-ca.sh validation, exercised exactly as the launch
#   invokes it, must accept a real cert (and still reject a genuinely marker-less one). Recommended
#   register action for the architect at dispatch: KEEP 69 (@scenario_hash:09f871cf8b99a34b),
#   ADD this scenario alongside it. The PO does not edit existing scenarios.
#
# HOW THE WORDING FORCES REAL-SHIPPED-SCRIPT FIDELITY (so the 3-cycle gap cannot recur):
#   (1) The validation under observation is BOUND, in a Given, to the one the real launch performs
#       by invoking the committed "agent-vault-ca.sh", exercised exactly as the launch invokes it on
#       the no-flag path — and EXPLICITLY excludes a reimplemented, modeled, or stand-in check that
#       re-derives the BEGIN-CERTIFICATE test differently from the shipped script. A fake/working
#       reimplementation cannot satisfy this Given.
#   (2) The observable is taken on a REAL no-flag bc-container launch, so the script that runs is the
#       shipped one; a unit harness that substitutes its own validation does not exercise this pin.
#   (3) The positive Then names the exact observed symptom — a validation-internal error
#       ("grep: unrecognized option" or any other) must NOT cause a valid cert to be misjudged —
#       so a grep-option (or any validation) defect in the shipped script RED-tests here.
#   The negative-limb example (genuinely marker-less content is rejected, fail-loud) keeps the fix
#   honest: it cannot degenerate to deleting the validation — the guard must still reject a real bad
#   cert. The two examples are the same single behavior (the shipped validation classifies the CA
#   correctly by the real BEGIN-CERTIFICATE marker), parameterized by input and expected outcome.
#
# COEXISTENCE the architect must enumerate at dispatch (by hash):
#   - scenario 69 (@scenario_hash:09f871cf8b99a34b) — END-STATE pin (CA file present at git's CA
#     path + proxied clone passes TLS). This scenario pins the VALIDATION-STEP fidelity that makes
#     69's end-state reachable on a real launch. Complementary; KEEP both, no supersede.
#   - scenario 68 (@scenario_hash:0d29c76818a323a1) — already superseded by 69 (fake-driver-only
#     fidelity); remains retired, unaffected by this scenario.
#   - templates scenario 200 (@scenario_hash:7ce09202755b0503) — broker delivers the root CA as
#     INLINE PEM CONTENT (producer/transport, ADR-045). Cross-BC complementary; unchanged.
#   - scenario 47 (@scenario_hash:6cb07698a874aa47) and the 45/46 broker family — broker
#     reachability / credential brokering; orthogonal to CA-VALIDATION at clone time. Unchanged.
#   - scenario 65 (@scenario_hash:bdec2754d9135086, F1) and scenario 67
#     (@scenario_hash:4154b0ea63d0516b, F2) — sequencing predecessors a real launch must clear
#     before the CA-validation step is reached. This pin presupposes both; the architect carries
#     the sequencing.
#
# Pin observable launch/validation behavior only (ADR-018; no BC source read) — the validation
# step's accept/reject decision, its diagnostics ("missing BEGIN CERTIFICATE", "grep: unrecognized
# option"), whether git is pointed at the CA, and whether the proxied clone runs are all observable
# from the real launch's behavior/output and the running container. @bc: and the reproducing
# @scenario_hash on dispatch are the Architect's; the block-only @scenario_hash below is the PO's
# authoring hash.
  @scenario_hash:3222fe1396f1ff53
  Scenario Outline: on a real no-flag bc-container launch, the committed agent-vault-ca.sh validation step exercised exactly as the launch invokes it classifies the materialized CA by the real BEGIN-CERTIFICATE marker, so a valid cert is accepted and the clone proceeds while a genuinely marker-less cert is rejected, and no validation-internal error misjudges a valid cert
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And the launched BC routes outbound HTTPS through the agent-vault MITM proxy via "HTTPS_PROXY", so the clone requires the broker root CA to verify TLS
    And the CA validation under observation is the one the real launch performs by invoking the committed "agent-vault-ca.sh", exercised exactly as the launch invokes it on the no-flag manifest-resolution path, and not a reimplemented, modeled, or stand-in check that re-derives the BEGIN-CERTIFICATE test differently from the shipped script
    And the agent-vault broker materializes the container CA bundle so that its on-disk content is <ca_content>
    When bc-container launch is run with BC name "shopsystem-test-harness" via the no-flag manifest-resolution clone path and the launch reaches its CA validation step
    Then the committed agent-vault-ca.sh validation step <validation_result>, with no "grep: unrecognized option" error and no other validation-internal error causing a valid cert to be misjudged
    And the launch <git_and_clone_outcome>

    Examples:
      | ca_content | validation_result | git_and_clone_outcome |
      | a real PEM certificate whose first line is exactly "-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----" | accepts the materialized CA and exits success, emitting no "agent-vault CA file missing BEGIN CERTIFICATE" diagnostic | points git at that CA file and the proxied clone of "shopsystem-test-harness" proceeds and completes its TLS handshake with no "error setting certificate file" error |
      | bytes that genuinely contain no "-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----" marker line anywhere | rejects the materialized CA and fails loud, naming the missing BEGIN CERTIFICATE marker | refuses to point git at the CA and the proxied clone does not run |
